<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-651-828  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 651 828.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC-Computing  August 1990 v3 n8 p54(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Corporate Voice is all style but very little substance. (SoftwareReview) (Scandinavian PC Systems Corporate Voice writing tool)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Janus, Susan.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Scandinavian PC Systems Inc. (products).andO;Product:   Corporate Voice (Computer program) (evaluation).andO;Topic:     Writing SkillsStyle CritiquingSoftware packagesEvaluation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Few organizations can claim a consistent writing style in memos, reports, andproposals.andP;  Documents produced in different departments might as well comefrom different companies.andP;  Corporate Voice, from Scandinavian PC Systems,tackles the problem by helping you develop a suitable and effective style forbusiness communications.andM;Though its intent is admirable, Corporate Voice carries the ball onlyhalfway.andP;  It easily flags writing that doesn't fit a specified style andpinpoints some problem sentences, but it fumbles when it issues tactics toimprove ineffective writing.andM;Billed as a &quot;style replicator,&quot; Corporate Voice builds a model for yourcorporate prose based on samples of writing you feed to it.andP;  It then comparesother writing with this model.andM;Building the model is the easy part.andP;  The hard part is helping poor writersimprove.andP;  The program's suggestions, like those of most grammar checkers andstyle analyzers, are just not useful, scarcely surprising when you considerhow difficult it is for people to teach effective writing.andP;  Advice such as&quot;Add vitality to your text by varying the structure of your sentences&quot; giveslittle solace to writers struggling to match the company's model of effectivewriting.andM;The program can play a useful role in developing a consistent corporatestyle.andP;  But don't trade a good editor for it.andP;  SUSAN JANUS</TEXT></DOC>